Alas, my bike club (of which Louis Garneau is an excellent sponsor) has
rules about representing sponsors in a good light to the public, so
rather than join the fun, I must point out that I really like my team
kit.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Accessories: Maybe zipping your booties will keep your feet warm and
&gt; dry, but it won't make those knobby tires give your street bike better
&gt; traction on the wet leaves scattered on that paved road.
">

I do feel compelled to point out the rider is on a cyclocross bike (note
brakes and top-tube cable routing, including extra-fancy 'cross-style
rear derailer cable), and unless I miss my guess, that's not a paved
road, that's a packed gravel road. Either that or it's a paved road with
a ridiculous amount of gravel scattered across its surface.

I would commend cyclocross to any cyclist, casual or competitive, as the
most fun one can have in bike shorts. Or bike tights. The bikes
themselves are a lot of fun to ride too: my new blanket recommendation
to newbies is to strongly consider a cheap 'cross bike as a veritable
Sawzall of bicycles: with the right tires and accessories, the bike can
tour, road race, commute, or even tackle surprisingly gnarly trails.

I went on a 'cross ride this week that detoured through a BMX track.
Even that was fun.

--
Ryan Cousineau rcous ... @sfu.ca http://www.wiredcola.com/
