Walking with poles can raise heart rate and engage more muscles than
walking at the same speed without poles -- it's a form of exercise.

Walking with poles is also used in training for skiing. My wife and I
do it a little as prep for skiing.  It's better than just walking,
though now I can see we are perhaps being mocked by people who think
the poles are fashion items.

I don't understand your mocking of the pictures in this online
catalog.

They look to me like images of people I could easily know, doing
things that I do or my acquaintances do in well-thought-out clothes
appropriate for the activity. At least one photo is, I think, of
someone I've met (I think it's Tim Johnson) a couple times.  The
photos are quite realistic for a line of clothing aimed toward people
involved in competitive cycling and skiing, as well as vigorous
outdoor recreation. The less sporty stuff -- like the city stuff --
looks good to me too.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;I expect that the manufacturing and the advertising departments are
&gt;separate. Indeed, I hope so.
">

Why hope so?

PS: I have no relationship to this company other than owning a couple
of hats made by them that are really nice, and a superb windbreaker by
them that's one of my favorite pieces of clothing.  And observing
their product on other cyclists and skiers.

--
JT
